column1: Notes related to the data in this spreadsheet

column2: Estimates are generated for British, EU+ and non-EU+ nationals' immigration and emigration. These are then added together to estimate the "All nationalities" totals. Calculations are done on unrounded estimates so the rounded numbers provided here may not always match this calculation exactly.
Net migration is calculated by subtracting emigration estimates from immigration estimates. We do this with unrounded estimates so the rounded numbers may not always match this calculation exactly.

Uncertainty intervals are provided for statistics created using mainly administrative data and some survey data. A wider interval indicates more uncertainty in the estimate.  
 
These uncertainty intervals have been constructed using simulation studies such that there is a 95% probability the intervals contain the true value, under the assumption that our simulations accurately include all the main sources of uncertainty.  

However, at the moment our uncertainty intervals should be interpreted with caution as our simulations do not measure all main sources of uncertainty and likely underreport uncertainty with international migration estimates. 

Currently, long-term international migration uncertainty intervals only quantify the doubt associated with adjustments to non-EU+ estimates, adjustments and temporal disaggregation to the EU+ estimates, as well as sampling error from IPS estimates for British nationals. Some main sources of uncertainty, like uncertainty associated with the administrative data, are not included. 

We are working to further improve our uncertainty measures so that they will cover a greater range of sources of uncertainty.

For consistency, all periods in table 3a and table 3b have been estimated using the latest method. This means that some estimates by nationality may differ from previously published estimates.

The reasons for immigration are the initial reasons for why individuals arrive in the UK. They do not show visas an individual may have transferred to.

Figures in table 3a and table 3b do not include those arriving via asylum and humanitarian resettlement routes, though British Nationals (Overseas) and Ukraine are included in the analysis that produced these figures. 

The estimates for All reasons are the sum of the estimates for the reasons presented. This calculation is done on unrounded figures so estimates by reason may not sum to the rounded estimate for All reasons.
Estimates in table 3a for YE December 2024 have been adjusted to account for early leavers.
Estimates by reason for immigration for non-EU+ nationals have been derived using Borders and Immigration data from the Home Office.

Reasons for immigration in table 4 are the initial reasons for why individuals arrive in the UK. They do not show visas an individual may have transferred to. 

The estimates for All reasons are the sum of the estimates for the reasons presented. This calculation is done on unrounded figures so the rounded estimates by reason may not sum to the rounded estimate for All reasons.

Tables 3a and 3b have data from year ending December 2021 only. This is because these numbers use our new methods for estimating non-EU+ nationals, which we have used from year ending June 2021 onwards.

Some time periods are marked as R. This means some of the estimates in this row have been revised. In this publication we have revised estimates for EU+ nationals and non-EU+ nationals from YE September 2023 to YE June 2024. No updates have been made to estimates of British nationals. These revisions are due to more available data, more information on Ukraine visas and improvements to how we estimate immigration and emigration of non-EU+ nationals.

Some time periods are marked as P. This means estimates in this row are provisional. You can read more about our provisional estimates in our methodology documents, please see the cover sheet for more information on these.

Figures for number of visas granted are from the Home Office, estimates from the Registration and Population Interaction Database (RAPID) and figures on National Insurance number (NINo) allocations are from the Department for Work and Pensions. Census 2021 data is from the Office for National Statistics.
 
ONS data on long-term immigration for non-EU+ nationals have been revised back to YE September 2023. RAPID data was previously revised back to YE June 2019 in the November 2024 publication. Census 2021 data, and figures on NINos and visas granted are for non-EU for all time periods have not been revised
 
The Census 2021 estimate is based on non-UK-born residents who arrived in England or Wales in the 12 months from March 2020 who intended to stay for 12 months or more, and the passport they held.
Estimates in table 3b for YE December 2024 have been adjusted to account for re-arrivals.
Estimates in table 3a and table 3b for this release do not follow our standardised revisions as they have been revised back to YE December 2021. Therefore, they will not match previous releases.

Home Office (HO) visas granted and ONS long-term immigration for non-EU+ nationals both exclude asylum and resettlement cases

HO visas granted excludes short-term and visit visas.

For the May 2025 release, we have updated our ONS long-term immigration for non-EU+ nationals in the comparisons across data sources visual to exclude asylum and resettlement cases. Therefore, this visual will be different to historical versions published.

RAPID data includes students and under 16s.
